TY  - JOUR
T1  - IS CEO PAY IN HIGH-TECHNOLOGY FIRMS RELATED TO INNOVATION?
AU  - Balkin, David B.
AU  - Markman, Gideon D.
AU  - Gomez-Mejia, Luis R.
Y1  - 2000/12/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/1556340
DO  - 10.5465/1556340
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1118
EP  - 1129
VL  - 43
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study uses the resource-based view of the firm and agency theory to examine the relationship between innovation and CEO pay in 90 high-technology firms. With firm size, performance, and other factors controlled, CEO short-term compensations was related to innovation as measured by number of patents and R&D spending. The data also suggest a less consistent temporal relationship between innovation and long-term CEO compensation in the high-technology firms. In a control sample of 74 low-technology firms, there was no relationship between innovation and either short- or long-term CEO pay.
AB  - This study uses the resource-based view of the firm and agency theory to examine the relationship between innovation and CEO pay in 90 high-technology firms. With firm size, performance, and other factors controlled, CEO short-term compensations was related to innovation as measured by number of patents and R&D spending. The data also suggest a less consistent temporal relationship between innovation and long-term CEO compensation in the high-technology firms. In a control sample of 74 low-technology firms, there was no relationship between innovation and either short- or long-term CEO pay.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/1556340
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/1556340
Y2  - 2026/04/24
