T1  - The Impact Of Collectivism And In-Group/Out-Group Membership On The Evaluation Generosity Of Team Members
AU  - Gómez, Carolina
AU  - Kirkman, Bradley L.
AU  - Shapiro, Debra L.
Y1  - 2000/12/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/1556338
DO  - 10.5465/1556338
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1097
EP  - 1106
VL  - 43
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In a scenario-based study using Mexican and U.S. samples, when a team member was perceived to be an in-group (rather than an out-group) member, collectivists evaluated that member significantly more generously than did individualists. Further, collectivists valued maintenance contributions more than individualists did, and individualists valued task contributions more than collectivists did. Nevertheless, both collectivists and individualists appeared to value an equity norm.
AB  - In a scenario-based study using Mexican and U.S. samples, when a team member was perceived to be an in-group (rather than an out-group) member, collectivists evaluated that member significantly more generously than did individualists. Further, collectivists valued maintenance contributions more than individualists did, and individualists valued task contributions more than collectivists did. Nevertheless, both collectivists and individualists appeared to value an equity norm.
